docs.abstract: The comedian and filmmaker on his Broadway show about not wanting to have a child – and what his daughter will think of it someday.
docs.snippet: The comedian and filmmaker on his Broadway show about not wanting to have a child – and what his daughter will think of it someday.
docs.lead_paragraph: Your one-man show, “The New One,” is about your not wanting to have a child, and then your struggles once you did. It’s also your first Broadway show, after a history of performing in smaller venues. How do you like being in a bigger theater? My recurring nightmare was me, onstage, in this 1,100-seat theater, with no people in it. I’ve had it ever since we even talked about doing the show on Broadway. Strangely enough, that became a reality in rehearsal, because it’s just the designers and the crew in the audience. There’s eight people in a room that seats 1,100, and so I do the show from start to finish with no laughter. It’s really empowering to live your nightmare.

headline.main: Mike Birbiglia Thinks You Don’t Know How to Tell a Story

docs.abstract: Could nasal breathing be more helpful for our brains than breathing through the mouth?
docs.snippet: Could nasal breathing be more helpful for our brains than breathing through the mouth?
docs.lead_paragraph: Folklore, spiritual traditions and even mothers have for ages drawn an implicit connection between respiration and state of mind: Breathe in deeply through your nose, we are told, to clarify thoughts, achieve serenity, defuse tantrums. There isn’t a lot of scientific evidence to back up these ideas, but a growing number of experiments have been looking at the influence that breathing has on our cognition. In October, a study in The Journal of Neuroscience considered the relationship between memory and how we breathe.

headline.main: Breathing Through the Nose May Offer Unique Brain Benefits

docs.abstract: A planet-spanning virtual observatory, years in the making, could change how we think about space, time and the nature of reality. Will it work?
docs.snippet: A planet-spanning virtual observatory, years in the making, could change how we think about space, time and the nature of reality. Will it work?
docs.lead_paragraph: We live 26,000 light-years from the center of the Milky Way. That’s a rounding error by cosmological standards, but still — it’s far. When the light now reaching Earth from the galactic center first took flight, people were crossing the Bering Strait land bridge, hunting woolly mammoths along the way.

headline.main: How Do You Take a Picture of a Black Hole? With a Telescope as Big as the Earth
